like, government,

596
00:30:38,167 --> 00:30:40,233
the semi-governmental groups,

597
00:30:40,267 --> 00:30:42,467
they dropped the ball.

598
00:30:42,500 --> 00:30:43,693
What was the problem, though?

599
00:30:43,700 --> 00:30:45,567
They weren't ready for it.

600
00:30:45,600 --> 00:30:48,133
The Rockaways, by design has
never been a place

601
00:30:48,167 --> 00:30:49,667
where there was a lot of
good investment

602
00:30:49,700 --> 00:30:51,567
or infrastructure anyway
to begin with.

603
00:30:51,600 --> 00:30:53,133
Why?
Look.

604
00:30:53,167 --> 00:30:57,867
This is what you would call
prime oceanfront property

605
00:30:57,900 --> 00:31:00,533
not far from New York City.

606
00:31:00,567 --> 00:31:01,833
What's going on?

607
00:31:01,867 --> 00:31:04,367
This was a place historically
where the city

608
00:31:04,400 --> 00:31:07,000
and Robert Moses in particular

609
00:31:07,033 --> 00:31:09,967
really used as, like, a dumping
ground for undesirable groups

610
00:31:10,000 --> 00:31:12,000
that the city didn't necessarily
want to deal with.

611
00:31:12,033 --> 00:31:14,200
Back in the day,
the Rockaways were

612
00:31:14,233 --> 00:31:16,867
a summer destination
for middle-class New Yorkers

613
00:31:16,900 --> 00:31:19,533
until better roads
and an improved rail system

614
00:31:19,567 --> 00:31:23,033
lured them to the beaches
of Long Island.

615
00:31:23,067 --> 00:31:26,033
They threw a bunch of
public housing projects in here.

616
00:31:26,067 --> 00:31:28,200
They sent a lot of the
low-income people of the city

617
00:31:28,233 --> 00:31:29,967
out here,
and it just wasn't a place

618
00:31:30,000 --> 00:31:32,333
that historically
the city ever took seriously.

619
00:31:32,367 --> 00:31:34,033
You know, since then,
we've always had

620
00:31:34,067 --> 00:31:36,533
a lot of working-class whites
move in,

621
00:31:36,567 --> 00:31:38,200
into more kind of
the western end,

622
00:31:38,233 --> 00:31:40,467
and so you've kind of seen
in the Rockaways

623
00:31:40,500 --> 00:31:43,567
just kind of shape out
along race and class lines.

624
00:31:43,600 --> 00:31:45,867
And the one dynamic
that's changed after Sandy

625
00:31:45,900 --> 00:31:48,367
was that a lot more, like,
young urban professional types,

626
00:31:48,400 --> 00:31:49,993
like, were really coming out
here, you know,

627
00:31:50,000 --> 00:31:51,367
maybe looking
intentionally or not

628
00:31:51,400 --> 00:31:53,567
to, like,
Brooklynify the Rockaways.

629
00:31:53,600 --> 00:31:54,367
Right.

630
00:31:54,400 --> 00:31:55,900
Or gentrify the Rockaways.

631
00:31:55,933 --> 00:31:58,067
Rockaway's called,
like, the Brooklyn Riviera

632
00:31:58,100 --> 00:31:59,333
or the Williamsburg Riviera.

633
00:31:59,367 --> 00:32:01,333
Who gets the shaft
in a situation like that?

634
00:32:01,367 --> 00:32:03,967
If you're a person
who's not a homeowner;

635
00:32:04,000 --> 00:32:06,333
if you're a person
that's struggling to pay rent,

636
00:32:06,367 --> 00:32:08,667
the plans are generally,
history has told us,

637
00:32:08,700 --> 00:32:10,000
gonna leave you behind.

638
00:32:10,033 --> 00:32:11,500
It's interesting
because I don't think

639
00:32:11,533 --> 00:32:13,060
